Our unofficial state bird, the Kirtland’s Warbler (Setophaga kirtlandii) from the jack pine barrens of northern Michigan. Once considered critically endangered, the species was delisted in October of 2019 after 52 years on the endangered species list. KIWAs are a fire dependent species, historically utilizing large tracts of young jack pine for nesting, resulting from large scale wildfires. Because of this limiting factor, this species likely never occurred in large numbers historically.

Although this is a conservation success story, it is one that comes with caveats. At present, KIWAs require large tracts of jack pine (300-500 acres). The state contracts timber companies to clear cut large tracts of older pine forest to give day to eventual planting of a jack pine monoculture. In many cases, these areas occur close to conifer swamps and stream corridors which house rare or declining herp species like wood turtles and massasauga rattlesnakes. Though some research has shown that massasaugas will utilize fresh clear cuts for summer habitat, logging operations will often level the landscape right up until the ground becomes too damp for heavy machinery to proceed without getting stuck. Since delisting, sometimes these clear cuts are seeded and other times they are just left to succeed on their own, which usually leads to rapid growth of thick aspen stands and makes them unusable for rare herp species. Unfortunately, single species management often has detrimental effects on an ecosystem scale.

#kirtlandswarbler #setophagakirtlandii #jackpine #landmanagement #habitat #puremichigan #endangeredspecies #birdphotography

Stinkpots are likely one of our most abundant turtles, though they’re infrequently seen because of their highly aquatic nature and reluctance to bask.

A beautiful female Eastern Massasauga (Sistrurus catenatus) basks at a gestation site in the Canadian shield region of Ontario. The gneiss and granite formations here provide drastically different upland habitat than I’m used to in Michigan, and females seek out large slabs and outcrops to cook babies over the summer months. In total, we observed 19 massasaugas over a three day period in a variety of locations. What an incredible place.

Was lucky enough to observe this female Eastern Massasauga (Sistrurus catenatus) and her fresh brood of neonates with @michigander_naturalist the other day. This is the second season in a row we’ve been able to see this up close, and it is never not an amazing thing to see. The photos aren’t the best, but we didn’t want to be too intrusive in a manner that would disturb either mom or her babies. It was just exciting to see them move about around her and on top of her outside of a mammal burrow. Minimizing disturbance on rattlesnakes can lead to exciting observations over time and provide some real insights into their secretive world.

#easternmassasauga #rattlesnake #sistruruscatenatus #massasauga #massasaugarattlesnake #neonate #birth #herping

A really nice Eastern Massasauga (Sistrurus catenatus) found on a forested ridge awhile back in southeast Michigan at a new location for me. The month of October has been brutal for us this year. The latter half of September and first few days of October brought a record breaking heat wave which kept temperatures in the mid to low 80s. Immediately afterward, a shift in the jet stream has kept cold air in the region for the better part of two weeks, with temps in the high 40s and low 50s. We also haven’t seen the sun for more than a few minutes for the past two and half weeks. Snakes are nowhere to be found as of late and it’s not looking like things are going to improve  whole lot. Numbers have been significantly low this fall, and I’m not even sure that a lot of individuals have made it back to their usual overwintering areas. Time will tell.

#easternmassasauga #rattlesnake #sistruruscatenatus #massasauga #massasaugarattlesnake #michigan #michiganwildlife #puremichigan

Though we were dealt a rotten hand when it comes to autumn  weather this year, the few nice days we’ve had gotten lots of snakes on the move. Walking forested ridges in the fall is among my favorite times of the year as it provides chances to see snakes in areas they don’t occupy for the rest of the year. Seeing a supposedly open-canopy wetland species in hardwood forest is always unique.

I was pretty excited to get some amazing looks at this Great Horned Owl (Bubo virginianus) this evening as the first snowflakes of the season began to fall. Happening to hear some back and forth hooting, I moved to an open snag and noticed this handsome bird staring back at me. The second owl was much higher up in the trees, but continued to call to its likely mate. Having good light and a vibrant backdrop is rare when it comes to owls, and this is easily the best shot I’ve ever taken of a GHOW.

And because you can’t have one without the other, here’s a Short-eared Owl (Asio flammeus) posted up along a ditch in the waning bits of daylight. Shorties work up and down these ditch lines where they hunt on the wing for voles and surprisingly, crayfish.

#shortearedowl #asioflammeus #owl #owlphotography #michigan #birding #birdphotography #michiganwildlife

A young Arizona Ridgenose Rattlesnake (Crotalus willardi) from the sky islands of Arizona. This snake was the second individual of the trip, and was an unexpected surprise while killing some time in a different range than the first one we saw came from.
